dingtonshire, Scotland","Seton, East Lothian, Scotland, United Kimgdom":"Seton, Haddingtonshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Sinclair","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and English: of Norman origin, a habitational name from Saint-Clair-sur-Elle (Manche), so called from the dedication of its church to Saint Clarus (see   Clare   3).","Americanized form of some similar (like-sounding) Jewish surname.","History: The Scottish family <i>Sinclair</i> (see 1 above) came to southern Scotland in the twelfth century from Huntingdonshire with the de Morvilles. Descendants of these Sinclairs became earls of Caithness in the 15th century. The frequency of the surname in Caithness and Orkney is largely due to the adoption by tenants of the name of their overlord."],"variants":[{"name":"Clare","meanings":["Irish (Clare, Wicklow, and Wexford): habitational name from Clare in Suffolk (an eastern county of England), the center of a major Norman baronial estate since the Norman Conquest. The English placename probably originated as a Celtic river name meaning ‘bright, gentle, or warm’. The surname is not from the Irish county name <i>Clare</i>, which is either from the surname or from a place called with Gaelic <i>clár</i> ‘plank bridge’. Another Norman surname in the southeast of Ireland was <i>de Clere</i>, from Clères in Seine-Maritime (France), named from the local river.","English and French: from the Middle English, Old French female personal name <i>Cla(i)re</i> (from Latin <i>Clara</i>, from <i>clarus</i> ‘clear, bright, famous’) which achieved some popularity, greater elsewhere in Europe than in England, through the fame of Saint Clare of Assisi (see   Chiara  ). The English surname seems to have been interchangeable with   Clear   1.","English: occupational name from an agent derivative of Middle English <i>cley</i> ‘clay’. The work of medieval clayers involved plastering a framework of interwoven twigs with mud to produce wattle-and-daub work."]},{"name":"St. Clair","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Sinclair  . This is also a French Canadian and American French altered form of the same surname.","French (<b>Saint-Clair</b>): habitational name from any of several places, e.g. in Normandy, named Saint-Clair (from the dedication of their churches to Saint Clarus). Compare   Saintclair  .","Haitian (also <b>Saint-Clair</b>): ornamental name or nickname, perhaps ironic, composed of French <i>saint</i> ‘saint’ or ‘holy’ and <i>clair</i> ‘clear’ or ‘lightness’. Alternatively, perhaps of the same French origin as 2 above. Compare   Saintclair  ."]}]},{"name":"Catherine","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."],"variants":[{"name":"Catheryn","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Katherine","meanings":["Variant of   Katherine ."]},{"name":"Catharin","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathrine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathryn","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathrin","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Catharine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Catherine Sinclair was born in 1310, in Scotland, United Kingdom, her father, Sir William Sinclair, was 30 and her mother, Lady Wiliam Sinclair, was 31. She married Sir William Seton, in 1329, in Haddingtonshire, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"1310–":"1310–Surnud","1310–Female":"1310–Surnud","1305–1333":"1305–1333","1323–1381":"1323–1381","1280–Male":"1280–Surnud","1280–Female":"1280–Surnud","1305":"1305","1323":"1323","1333":"1333","1310":"1310","1381":"1381","1329":"1329","1280":"1280","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Haddingtonshire, Scotland","Seton, East Lothian, Scotland, United Kimgdom":"Seton, Haddingtonshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1310–":"1310–Kuollut","1310–Female":"1310–Kuollut","1305–1333":"1305–1333","1323–1381":"1323–1381","1280–Male":"1280–Kuollut","1280–Female":"1280–Kuollut","1305":"1305","1323":"1323","1333":"1333","1310":"1310","1381":"1381","1329":"1329","1280":"1280","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Haddingtonshire, Scotland","Seton, East Lothian, Scotland, United Kimgdom":"Seton, Haddingtonshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Scotland":"Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1310–":"1310–Décédée","1310–Female":"1310–Décédée","1305–1333":"1305–1333","1323–1381":"1323–1381","1280–Male":"1280–Décédé","1280–Female":"1280–Décédée","1305":"1305","1323":"1323","1333":"1333","1310":"1310","1381":"1381","1329":"1329","1280":"1280","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Écosse, Royaume-Uni","Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Haddingtonshire, Écosse","Seton, East Lothian, Scotland, United Kimgdom":"Seton, Haddingtonshire, Écosse, Royaume-Uni","Scotland":"Écosse, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Lady Catherine Sinclair est née en 1310, à Écosse, Royaume-Uni, son père, Sir William Sinclair, avait 30 ans et sa mère, Lady Wiliam Sinclair, avait 31 ans. Elle a épousé Sir William Seton, en 1329, à Haddingtonshire, Écosse. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille. Elle est décédée dans sa ville natale."},"de":{"1310–":"1310–Verstorben","1310–Female":"1310–Verstorben","1305–1333":"1305–1333","1323